ps://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLe4PRejZgr0PzN7r8NikAnOqP70DHhoJ0" target="_blank" rel="noopener">YouTube</a>和<a href="http://www.bloomberg.com/podcasts/masters-in-business/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Bloomberg 上流</a>式传输和下载我们的完整对话，包括任何播客附加内容。您可以<a class="gtrackexternal" href="https://plnk.to/MIB?to=page">在此处找到</a>我们在您最喜爱的播客主机上发布的所有早期播客。</p><p style="text-align: center;"> ~~~</p><p>播音员：这里是彭博电台 Barry Ritholtz 的商业硕士课程。</p><p> BARRY RITHOLTZ，主持人，商业大师：本周在播客上，我有一位额外的特邀嘉宾。 Mathieu Chabran 是总部位于巴黎的另类资产管理公司 TIKEHAU Capital 的联合创始人。他们管理着价值超过 400 亿美元的资产。</p><p>我发现这真的是一次关于从不同角度接近投资世界的精彩对话。富有创造力，跳出框框思考，不仅要模仿别人的做法，还要通过以不同的方式思考世界来创造新的机会。</p><p>谈话内容丰富，引人入胜。我觉得这很棒，我想你也会，不用多说，我与 TIKEHAU Capital 的 Mathieu Chabran 的谈话。</p><p> TIKEHAU CAPITAL 联合创始人 MATHIEU CHABRAN：谢谢你，Barry。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：我忘了说，您已于 2022 年 1 月获得法兰西共和国总统颁发的法国荣誉军团骑士勋章。我们将在其他时间回过头来讨论。我不知道这与资产管理有多大关系，但让我们谈谈你在受到法国总统称赞之前所做的事情。</p><p>你在巴黎上学，但你在伦敦的美林和德意志银行开始了你的职业生涯。告诉我们一些关于那个背景的信息。</p><p> CHABRAN：是的，不，巴里，没错。你知道，这在欧洲是一回事，我实际上认为，伦敦仍然是你加入金融服务业时想要接触的地方。所以我很幸运能够在 90 年代后期在美林公司获得这个暑期实习机会。我遇到了安托万，实际上是我的共同创始合伙人。所以那是有一段时间了，但尽管如此，我不知道是不是一见钟情，但我们相处得很好，在投资银行工作了几年后，他加入了高盛。实际上，我加入了德意志银行。我们决定自己尝试一下。我们分别是 28 岁和 30 岁。</p><p>回顾过去，投资银行业务，即使银行已经不复存在，也是一次很棒的培训。我认为这是一次很棒的培训。我想我们学到了很多东西。你在投资银行业的风险敞口，我的背景是杠杆金融银行家。 90 年代后期，欧洲高收益市场的出现，你会以前所未有的方式印制交易。你得到了这种曝光，你是一个年轻的分析师，助理，你可以和管理团队一起参加路演。我回头看，就我们所获得的曝光度而言，这是一次地狱般的训练。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：是的，我可以想象。你在巴黎上学时的计划是一直进入金融领域，还是你最初倾向于另一个方向？</p><p> CHABRAN：在加入巴黎的一所商学院之前，我在我的家乡普罗旺斯艾克斯学习政治学。当时没有迹象表明我会进入金融领域。</p><p>因此，当我接触到优秀的老师并开始学习时，顺便说一下，什么，又一次，回到 90 年代后期，但后来你开始读书，我不是在谈论理论书籍，但是一些经验，人们，我记得这些书，读过迈克尔刘易斯的“说谎者的扑克牌”，读过关于米尔肯和垃圾债券的“掠夺者的舞会”，这就是兴奋的开始。你就像，我必须接触到这一点。</p><p>所以不，没有写任何东西，但这是重要的一步。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：快进到今天。你现在在美国的一家大型欧洲公司工作，但实际上你的职业生涯是在伦敦的大型美国公司开始的。</p><p>查布兰：没错。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：美国公司在欧洲与欧洲公司在美国的文化差异是什么？</p><p> CHABRAN：是的，这是一个有趣的问题。从美国的角度来看，巴里，有时，欧洲可能是一个简单的概念，但它是一个非常复杂的现实。所以在欧洲做生意显然是本地化，因为意大利不是西班牙，法国不是德国。有时，伦敦人认为他们涵盖了整个欧洲运动场，但这又是一个复杂的现实。</p><p>因此，当时遇到了为这些美国银行工作的美国人，现在他们明白了。那些成功的人，甚至我们的一些同行、竞争对手、朋友、正在竞争和攻占欧洲市场的美国特许经营商，通常那些成功或非常成功的人是那些在实地花了很多时间的人.</p><p>然后相反，希望，在为美国特许经营工作，与人和伟大的导师共度时光，你知道，对我来说，我现在希望能更好地理解我们在这里扩张时的文化差异。我相信您会喜欢，在纽约与美洲其他地方的现实情况截然不同，部分原因在于拜访美国中西部地区的新客户。</p><p>所以希望这里有一点融合，让它变得有价值。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：我喜欢 Spalding Gray 的那句老话，“我不住在美国，我住在美国东海岸的一个小岛上。”因为就您而言，纽约不是堪萨斯城，堪萨斯城也不是迈阿密。但纽约绝对是它自己的生物。</p><p> CHABRAN：这是肯定的。你知道，对于我们 TIKEHAU 来说，这是在北美开设和扩张的重要一步。只是背景，巴里，当我五年前的今年 2018 年搬到这里时，我们在北美几乎没有任何关系。我们从客户的角度，从 LP 的角度进行了一些投资和关系。 And fast forward, today is close to 10 percent of our AUM that we have raised here. We launched new initiatives, we try to be differentiating. And obviously it&#39;s a long-term game and you have to be definitely long-term greedy when you set up a business in the US.</p><p> But in the business we&#39;re in today, the alternative asset management space, as competitive as it can be, but the structural opportunity now is such that the commitment as a European that you have to make here has to be long term. I made the commitment personally, and I can see the path because there is room to expand the business.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So let&#39;s talk about what led to the decision to launch TIKEHAU Capital back in 2004. You&#39;re at Deutsche Bank, your colleague Antoine is at Goldman Sachs. What made you say, “Hey, let&#39;s get the band back together again?”</p><p> CHABRAN: Well, you know what, it&#39;s actually back to what I was just saying. We were watching all these franchises being launched, and obviously at the top of them and all the ones you can think of who are leading the industry today, but back then they were managing a few tens of billions of dollars, which was enormous back then, but it&#39;s only a fraction of what they are today.</p><p> And we were seeing all these American franchises launching in Europe, out of London, and we were like, “Why don&#39;t we give it a go?” We learned leverage finance, we learned real estate debt, we knew high yield, we knew opportunistic investment and we&#39;re like, it&#39;s never too late, it&#39;s never too early and we decided to go with a huge $4 million AUM that we had gathered from friends and family.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> CHABRAN: So you can appreciate the challenge back then but you have to start somewhere.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right. That&#39;s walking around cash back then.</p><p> So let&#39;s talk about not too late, not too early, you launch right after the dot-com implosion.</p><p> CHABRAN: Correct.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: But a few years before the great financial crisis …</p><p> CHABRAN: That&#39;s right.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: What was that period like, what was that lull like between those two giant volatility events?</p><p> CHABRAN: It was an experience because the dot-com bubble, I remember being a young associate at Merrill Lynch, and all the investment banks, they had to reinvent themselves to make sure they could remember this retained talent that we&#39;ve been hearing lately again.</p><p> So they were creating some cool working space and you would no longer wear a tie and all that, which was all form of a substance and as if there was a shift. And then you have this ramp up from effective year four when we launched to the GFC and we&#39;re three years, four years into business at TIKEHAU. And I remember we feel extreme pride because then we were banking with Bear Stearns, we were banking with Lehman Brothers, and that was a step in the entrepreneurial development. And then all of a sudden, over the weekend, those banks are gone.</p><p> And so you&#39;re like a young entrepreneur leaving this near-death experience, despite thinking that you were close to certainty because you were working with the best institution and counterpart you can think of. And then all of a sudden, it&#39;s all about how you see and look at the world, never take anything for granted, always be in the world of challenging everything.</p><p> So it&#39;s not good for your stomach pain every morning, but only the paranoid survive. And I think that was a great learning experience.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So let&#39;s talk about what took place post Bear Stearns and post Lehman from a business perspective. Bear Stearns gets absorbed into JPMorgan Chase. So your contacts at Bear Stearns are still in business.</p><p> The best parts of Lehman Brothers get absorbed into Barclay. So I got to imagine a lot of the folks you were doing business with at those places landed on their feet and you still had some relationship or am I being too sanguine about it?</p><p> CHABRAN: No, no, that was a bit of all of the above. But more importantly for us in our development, as I said, it was about never taking anything for granted. Because Lehman Brothers is what, a single-A rated bank on the Friday night and it&#39;s defaulted you know, on the Monday morning, and even if I&#39;m sketching a bit, from there on, at the time, we&#39;re 800 million AUM, I guess. We have a team of 20, 25 people, most of them still being with us today, by the way. And it&#39;s great when you&#39;ve been to work together, if you allow me, because then you just have to look at someone in the eyes and you know exactly how they&#39;re going to behave, because we&#39;ve been through that together.</p><p> And so for us, beyond the people and beyond the institution, It was the beginning of the second phase of the journey. I&#39;d like to say maybe less naive about how easy all these things are, because they&#39;re not easy. Steve Schwarzman wrote his book. It&#39;s called “What It Takes.” And so for us, that was, everything being equal, the beginning of the second phase of the journey, where it was no longer the teasing part.</p><p> You were effectively into the real stuff.</p><p> Now, on the positive and the silver lining was that this whole situation started putting a lot of light on, let&#39;s say, the alternative market. Private debt, private credit was unheard of in Europe until the banks effectively went into this massive liquidity squeeze and all those asset managers had to step in and fill this void. Great opportunity for us. Private equity at the time was only about buyout and LBO. Only few had heard about the growth equity part where you need to strengthen an entrepreneurial company&#39;s balance sheet because it&#39;s not, well she&#39;s not trying to sell the business, it&#39;s just about making sure you find the right partners to strengthen the balance sheet. And so on and so forth.</p><p> We started a new period adding on top of that this very accommodating monetary policy where that was the beginning of a new chapter for private markets. And we were lucky to effectively embark on this journey at this time.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So let me follow up on the financial crisis, the period afterwards. Clearly it was highly disruptive, lots of damage done, lots of people lost their jobs, lots of businesses went out, but it sounds like a lot of opportunities were created in what came after.</p><p> CHABRAN: It was certainly the case for us. Again, many challenges, but with the hard work and with people who could see the opportunity and possibly with a European approach thinking that, yes, you can develop a very multi-local footprint organization in Europe, be an alternative to global investors, to clients, to the one established, mainly Americans, I must admit. That was very exciting. It was very exciting to get into that. And to a certain extent, we had been looking forward for the day where we could face another of those crises.</p><p> And we all know they&#39;re all different, but better prepared.有了更多的资源，有了更强大的平台，有了更大的足迹，有了更好的准备，把 COVID 放在一边，把 Brexit 放在一边，在过去 10 年、12 年里把所有这些小步骤都放在一边，我们一直在为什么时候做好更好的准备周期变化。</p><p>我们可能已经进入这个新周期的新篇章，提高利率，从一年前开始，我们认为它不会很快降低。因此，我们回到我们工作的基础，风险承保、风险评估、资产价格与资产估值不同。</p><p>我的意思是估值是以无风险利率贴现的未来现金流加上风险溢价。你猜怎么着？现在的无风险利率为 5% 不再为零，风险溢价比之前的 2% 更接近 5%。</p><p>所以突然之间，我们工作的全部优点又回到了球场的中心，这让我们的工作更加令人兴奋。</p><p>过去 12 个月以来，我们对今天的投资感到无比兴奋。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：让我们谈谈是什么将 TIKEHAU 带到了美国。显然你们在欧洲非常成功。您现在在全球拥有 13 个办事处。仅仅是美国市场的规模吗？这里的吸引力是什么？</p><p> CHABRAN：嗯，我的意思是，规模绝对是一个原因。但我要补充一点，我们当时刚刚上市，2017 年。对我们来说，上市可能远在近年来变得更加普遍之前，上市障碍的主要目标实际上是推广品牌，专营权。在 60 年代之际，我们从未出售过一股股票。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：你们只允许一小部分公开，对吧？</p><p> CHABRAN：是的，没错。我们所有的历史支持者、股东，他们实际上一直在支持我们的业务。我们两次进入 ECM 市场，他们都加强了他们的所有权。因此，与许多 IPO 不同，IPO 是一种通过业务获利的方式，对我们来说，这实际上是关于使平台合理化。正如你所提到的，我们刚刚经历了 13、14 年的创业发展，这段时间非常坎坷。因此，这是一种使平台合理化的好方法，一个品牌，一个名字，让这个名字在那里。</p><p>那是在 2017 年，我们在巴黎泛欧交易所上市。来到美国，除了在某个时候来到美国别无选择。我们认为时机是正确的，因为我们现在和那时都有 200 亿资产管理规模。我们已经在亚洲工作了几年，而且前途无量。所以我决定来这里推广这个品牌，转化为商业关系，为美国投资者筹集更多资金，就你而言，美国是世界上最深的市场之一。</p><p>然后也开始在美国这里部署资本。</p><p>并不是说绝对没有资金短缺，而是正如我们喜欢在 TIKEHAU 所说的那样，创造而不是竞争。所以我们开始了像二级私人信贷这样的倡议。私人债务是这里的主流发展战略，我指的是全球和美国。我认为我们是最早进入二级私人信贷的公司之一。</p><p>快进几年，三年，现在我们可以展示战略的优点，战略的记录。我们开始扩展到中端市场基础设施。那是在拜登大选之前，当我们在欧洲的基础设施领域并不活跃时，所有的注意力都集中在基础设施上。</p><p>因此，我们试图找到一些可以让我们与众不同的游戏，不仅是相对于欧洲和亚洲投资者，而且是在美国，能够向 LP 讲述一个不同的故事，其中一个关键的差异化因素是皮肤我们作为组织的结构和创始人所拥有的游戏。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：所以很多上市的公司都拥有可用于收购的有价值的货币。这对思考有何影响？</p><p> CHABRAN：是的，没错，自上市以来我们非常有选择地使用了几次。 Infra 是其中之一，另一个是欧洲的房地产。我的意思是，他们是非常有选择性的补强收购。在我们的业务中进行收购总是一个大赌注，对吗？我们从事人事业务，你需要化学反应，我的意思是，你需要文化来解决问题。</p><p>但展望未来，可以肯定的是，与几年前相比，我们今天在反收购方面处于更有利的地位。因此，随着市场和行业的重组，我们肯定会非常机会主义。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这很有趣，Bolt On 的想法与在同一空间内的想法不同。由于化学反应，由于文化问题，金融收购的历史由来已久，但效果并不理想。</p><p> CHABRAN: That&#39;s right.</p><p> RITHOLTZ：但是你之前说的话真的让我印象深刻。你想创造，而不是竞争。那么，让我们来谈谈你们在 TIKEHAU 的人如何以不同的方式思考，告诉我们，或者用史蒂夫·乔布斯的话说，思考不同，告诉我们你们如何以不同于许多竞争对手的方式对待世界。</p><p>查布兰：是的。你知道当我们开始的时候，正如我告诉过你的那样，非常谦虚，即使你与私人投资者、高净值人士、家族办公室交谈，也有很多特许经营权，他们在接近他们的方式上可以更灵活一点资产配置，他们需要找到一个理由，为什么他们会选择当时的 TIKE-who，而不是 TIKEHAU。</p><p>里索尔兹：（笑声）</p><p> CHABRAN：并找到他们会在那里分配的原因。</p><p>回到欧洲，回到过去，当我们开始进行私人信贷、直接贷款时，今天是非常主流的。我可以告诉你，那时候不是。当时，他们甚至在欧洲称之为影子银行。</p><p>里索尔兹：是的。</p><p> CHABRAN：自从我上次阅读影子银行以来已经有一段时间了，因为它在今天变得如此主流和结构化，以至于它确实是一年中的一部分。</p><p>所以我们一直试图有效地成为一点点，我不知道它是怎么出现的，它不是失败者，而是带来一些不同的东西，这样你就可以 -</p><p> RITHOLTZ：清白？</p><p> CHABRAN：是的，这样你就可以为自己出名，然后利用这些相邻的业务来扩大规模，使它们成为主流。我是说我们几年前在纽约推出的二级私人信贷现在正变得更加主流。</p><p>每天我都会看到其中一家大型膨胀支架银行启动或谈论该计划。我们就像，好吧，也许那是我们的好主意。顺便说一句，竞争是好的。竞争没有错，但至少你已经为自己树立了名声。很明显，你有记录，你可以展示它。</p><p>这是第一步。</p><p>第二件事，巴里，如果可以的话，在我们的行业中，最大的不同应该是经理们在他们的业务中投入的游戏皮肤。</p><p>我想说的是，在我们这个行业，你会遇到很多愿意用别人的钱赚钱的人。你会遇到越来越少的人愿意用他们孩子的钱来赚钱。任何企业家都在通过借入一些资金并投资于他的业务来承担风险，无论业务是什么。</p><p>在我们的行业中，有时我认为我们在游戏中展示皮肤的方式有点讽刺，更不用说虚伪了。我不认为附带利益是一种很好的利益一致性。唯一的利益一致是任何给定的经理或公司投入其基金的资本金额。</p><p>当你读到的时候，好吧，好吧，我们把基金的 1% 作为 GP 的承诺，那是十亿，你知道，我们投入了 1000 万，这是很多钱，是的，但你收取 2%未来10年，所以期权成本不会那么高。</p><p>当您将 10%、20% 的资产负债表资本与您的 LP 并排放置时，您可以做一个基本的 Excel 电子表格，您会看到，您知道，什么是利害攸关的，而且那有效地，是的，您将通过管理费和附带权益的业绩费赚一些钱，但你知道，你与客户并肩面临的风险是完全不同的。</p><p>我认为这是该行业应该走向的方向。而我们的许多同行、竞争对手，他们都有不同的模式。但顺便说一句，巴里，来自 GP、合作伙伴、资产负债表和上市的那个在游戏中有重要皮肤的人是我们加强这个股权基础的好方法，这是合作伙伴自己的和控制和管理自己，有效地创造了迄今为止，在欧洲绝对首屈一指的皮肤游戏模式。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：我喜欢这听起来的方式。让我们谈谈欧洲。</p><p>如果我们回顾过去几十年，欧洲在 2000 年代的表现优于美国，当时我们正在经历互联网泡沫和金融危机。在 2010 年代，美国市场刚刚火起来，而且表现非常好。 2020 年代的事情开始有点不稳定。您如何比较过去几十年欧洲与美国的投资环境？</p><p> CHABRAN：很明显，它们都是由利率驱动的，它们使你知道方向相同，但模式不同，当我们几年前在欧元危机的背景下首次在欧洲实行负利率时，你知道这是全球金融危机首先是主权国家，但后来你知道，在 IG 市场和投资大市场的权利下，企业基本上借了 100 美元，并被要求偿还 98 美元。</p><p>今天当你回头看，没有回头交易，你会想，好吧，我们当时在想什么？因为对于我们所做的事情，我的意思是，你知道业务，巴里，就像风险承保一样，是关于有效地扩大风险和回报。我们处在一个非常尴尬的环境中。</p><p>这就是为什么我很惊讶看到这么多人感到惊讶。你知道，一年前，也就是 5 月 22 日，利率开始上升，突然间整个软件都被窃听了。</p><p>我的意思是，我们所做的不是火箭科学。这一切都归结为流动性价值和信贷成本。然后我们可以开始，你知道，做我们应该做的事情，你知道，风险承保。因此，欧洲、美国在下降的过程中进入了不同的模式，在上升的过程中则截然不同。</p><p>我的意思是，在美国这里，很明显，你们在加息方面更加积极，在我看来这是正确的。也许欧洲当时有点落后。他们实际上更快地降低利率，甚至降到负利率。</p><p>但是现在正在发生一些脱钩。对我们来说，这是一个很好的方式，特别是在 TIKEHAU，我们非常容易接触到收益游戏、信贷、基础设施、房地产、定制信贷。因此，所有这些都是风险承保的起点。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：那么让我们谈谈 2010 年代和 2020 年代之间的区别，首先，嘿，很有争议的是，当美联储开始在美国加息时，他们已经落后于曲线。他们 2% 的目标已在一年前达到，CPI 继续走高。</p><p>因此，如果美联储落后于曲线，那么欧洲中央银行在处理通胀问题方面落后了多少？</p><p> CHABRAN：美国和欧洲的中央银行可能有不同的授权。一个可能比其他的更具政治性，有时当你必须有效地为所有赤字融资时，你必须注意你需要能够发行和偿还这笔债务。</p><p>我认为，就目前而言，在不涉及太多政治细节的情况下，我的意思是，相对于他们对 COVID 的反应或 10 年前你知道的欧元危机的反应，欧洲可能不是一个好地方。我的意思是欧洲的政治局势可能间接地对欧洲央行产生了一些影响，正如你所知道的那样，我的意思是克里斯蒂娜拉加德在马里奥德拉吉之后一直做得非常出色，但该机构可能应该在你的方式上更大胆一些&#39;重新解决这个通货膨胀问题。</p><p>因为我们都知道，一段非常低的利率会造成巨大的不平等。获得信贷的人与无法获得信贷的人之间的不平等。当我说人时，它是个人的，是公司的，是国家的。具有讽刺意味的是，你拯救了一个系统，但你让这个系统在人们走出这个时期的方式上变得更加不平等。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这真的很有趣。在利率极低的后金融危机时代，任何以信贷、房地产、股票、债券定价的东西都表现非常好。当然，这有助于美国前 10% 的人。在 COVID 期间，我们看到了大规模的财政反应，而不仅仅是货币反应，这似乎对整个经济阶层，尤其是中产阶级都有帮助。那么，我们在金融危机后和 COVID 后的经历如何告诉我们需要在货币和财政刺激之间取得平衡？</p><p>是的，你完全正确。但出于同样的原因，我们知道现在，我不是经济学家，但在美国，在欧洲，通货膨胀，结构性通货膨胀，人们可能对此有不同的看法，肯定会伤害那些有更少的资源。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> CHABRAN：显然，食品、能源、住房，甚至不谈学校、医疗保健，显然在欧洲，我们在这个问题上的环境完全不同。</p><p>所以这是一个棘手的情况，我认为资产经理可以发挥作用的地方是确保无论何时有人存钱或投资 10 亿美元，无论是私人投资者还是大型机构投资者，是否有合适的与正在实施的战略相关的风险回报。</p><p>在零利率环境下，这非常复杂，因为每个人都掷骰子，结果是双六，因为只有在有钱的时候你才能做对。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> CHABRAN：因为当钱是免费的时候，投资就没有价值。既然我们处于金钱具有一定价值的情况下，那么你就可以有所区别了，这应该再次使个人节省一美元或仅投资十亿美元的机构受益。</p><p>而且，在这方面，无论这种宏观形势如何，如果我回到我们作为资产管理者的角色，那就是我们可以发挥作用的地方。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：那么让我们谈谈与风险和回报相关的估值。可以说，今天的美国，无论是公开市场还是私人市场，都不便宜。它们在互联网上并不昂贵，但肯定不便宜。欧洲和世界其他地区在估值基础上与美国相比如何？</p><p> CHABRAN：也许因为我来自杠杆金融背景，就像我告诉过你的那样，我倾向于总是关注不利因素。但我也在此过程中了解到，作为一家公司，你很少死于损益或资产，但你总是死于负债。</p><p>而且我认为，实际上这种非常便宜的资金过剩，这种杠杆过剩，这种认为你可以无限期地无限期获得廉价到免费资本的过度想法可能在某些地方造成了一些错误的资产配置模式.</p><p>所以我认为我们现在已经进入了一个时期，我们必须吞下所有定价错误、过度杠杆化的资产。公司信贷是其中之一，显然是债券，我指的是主权债券市场，我们记得 SVB 的故事，它是关于国库券的。</p><p>然后你，显然是房地产，许多领域以错误的成本过度杠杆化。这可能是痛苦的，因为必须有人承受痛苦，即使与 2008 年不同，风险集中在银行的资产负债表上，如今风险更多地分散在资产管理公司身上。但你必须找到一种方法来耗尽所有这些过剩的流动性，一方面这是必要的，但另一方面可能定价错误。</p><p>所以今天，我认为 IG 固定利率公司债券市场的一部分，显然是房地产的一部分，我们一直在详细讨论这一点，我们必须以某种方式承受一些痛苦或损失，或者形式。</p><p>一如既往，在这种交易的另一边，这将为那些流动性强、灵活的人创造巨大的机会，他们不必携带陈旧的库存，如果我可以说的话。</p><p>我的印象是，美国的做法会更加现实，即承受压力、承受痛苦并重新开始。在欧洲，也许有一点预转和延长游戏，但总比最终必须完成的事情立即完成要好。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：撕掉创可贴，别等了。</p><p> CHABRAN：没错，这就是我们在金融风险和金融定价方面应该做的。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：所以你提到过剩的流动性正在导致过度和混乱。美联储利率和世界其他地区的利率更高，利率更高，将其中的一些从系统中移除，并且结合起来，已经倒闭的区域银行的影响是什么，其中一些，但它肯定已经对上帝的恐惧进入了很多，你们这些小银行商店，这对那里所有的过剩流动性有什么影响？</p><p> CHABRAN：你知道，关于区域性银行，我不想发表评论，我不是专家，令人惊讶的是大型、非常大型的机构会如此迅速地陷入流动性压力。再次回到我的评论，这是你的责任方。那里有很多评论。</p><p>我看到的是，对于资产管理者来说，这是一个非常有趣的结构性机会，因为它在市场方面创造了一些空白，我们可以通过某种方式、形状或形式来填补。所以我认为从积极的方面来说，投资者、分配者。</p><p>如今，他们可以有效地将资本分配到战略中，从而对其投资组合产生复合效应。因为我不知道，两年前在某些策略中是 3、4%，现在可以是 8 到 10。</p><p>因此，当你开始将你的新配置复合到这些类型的策略中时，这可以弥补你的投资组合中由于利率上升而本身可能有点低的部分。再次，信贷，房地产，你有什么。所以这是积极的。你必须能够做到这一点，对吗？那么你是怎么做到的呢？我的意思是，如果你实际上有人们一直在谈论的分母效应，或者更多的流动性限制，因为现金没有像你预期的那样迅速返回，因为你的经理不能出售他们的投资组合。</p><p>例如，二级市场在私募股权方面一直在疯狂发展。正如我所说，私人信贷是另一回事。考虑到那里的资金量，房地产将是一个显而易见的问题。</p><p>所以这是准备说，好吧，我已经在这个策略上赚了百分之五、六、七，也许我会退出这个策略，尽管打折，尽可能低，但收益将能够是再投资于将产生更高回报的策略，在中短期内可以弥补我对我的养老金领取者或你有什么的现金流需求。</p><p>所以我实际上非常乐观，所有资产所有者、资产配置者都可以变得灵活。这是一个非常激动人心的时刻。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：让我们谈谈 TIKEHAU 拥护者如何影响投资。显然，目标是实现某种可持续发展的未来。你的投资主题是什么？</p><p>查布兰：是的。我认为我们在已经成为非常主流的战略方面相对较早，你知道，这是正确的，这确实是许多因素的结合。我们在 2017-2018 年推出了我们的第一个增长型私募股权战略，正如我所说，远早于它成为许多经理人和许多配置者的必备战略。</p><p>我们开始这样做是因为在欧洲，我们一直在与企业家、家族一起投资，正如我所说，我们不是一家收购商店，我们不控制，我们不杠杆化公司，我们正努力，作为资产所有者和公司之间的中间人，在我们看到金融游戏的地方进行分配，但这是一个有影响力的金融游戏。因此，当我们在 1718 年开始实施这一战略，并开始分配资本，投资于有解决方案的企业家时，必须大规模实施。因为当你想在减少二氧化碳排放的气候方面实现这些目标时，投资于到 2050 年将发生变化的东西是很好的，但更重要的是找到今天有效的东西并将其大规模化。</p><p>放大。我们正在投资盈利为 2000 万、2500 万、5000 万的 EBITDA 和所需资金的中型市场公司。这些人不打算出售他们的公司，他们需要资金来扩大规模。我们开始在低碳交通、建筑物的能源效率方面这样做。如您所知，它占绿色气体排放量的 40%。所以我们开始这样做，我自然会说，五年后，我们现在可以有效地代表案例研究。显然，业绩记录很重要，但当我们谈论这种影响力投资时，人们想了解我们在谈论什么。</p><p>这是关于气候的。</p><p>然后我们启动了再生农业战略，因为关键目标之一是如何捕获碳，而没有什么比土壤和地面更能帮助做到这一点了。那是在股权方面。</p><p>然后我们开始进行一些私人信贷影响融资。这意味着什么？你是借款人，我们以 5% 的利率借给你一些钱，你是 EBITDA 的三倍，我们采用财务分析的所有传统信用指标，然后我们添加第三个维度。如果你达到了某些目标、某些目标、额外的财务目标，那么你将提高你的资金成本。如果你有效地证明你减少了 X 或 Y 或者改变了这个生产过程，你的 5% 的优惠券将下降到 4。</p><p>突然间，您意识到，如果您的资金成本下降，那么由于实现了一些额外的财务目标，您的股本回报率就会上升。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> CHABRAN：所以你可以证明这不是慈善事业。这是关于确保我们使用可用资金将其发送到有意义的地方，然后所有利益相关者都能从中受益。就在五年前，很高兴再次创造而不是竞争，我们正在努力推动这一点。</p><p>今天，这是没有商量余地的。与我们的 LP 没有商量余地。与我们的客户、我们的合作伙伴、我们的银行、我们的客户、我们的员工巴里没有商量余地。我的意思是，当我们与一些 20 多岁、30 多岁的同事、专业人士交谈时，这是他们对公司承诺的一部分。</p><p>因为你知道的一个大问题，当涉及到这种影响和 ESG 时，让我们从更广泛的意义上说，充其量你会遇到非常机会主义，最坏的情况你会遇到假的。在这两种情况下，都不好。</p><p>因此，我们、我们的同事、我们的员工、员工和所有利益相关者，我的意思是，他们是监护人，他们是我们在这里真实存在的管家。再说一次，现在它不再是可有可无，而是必须拥有，而且只有一种方法。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：所以 ESG 似乎在欧洲找到了很多支持。您对这在美国如何变得政治化感到有点惊讶吗？他们似乎是一群反对影响力投资和可持续投资的人，不是因为回报，而是他们不喜欢其中的政治色彩。</p><p>查布兰：是的。我并不感到惊讶，因为我再次成为这里的外星人，但我试图成为美国政治动态的观察者。我们甚至亲身经历过。我们的一些 LP 通常由不同的董事会组成，有些是教师、消防员、警察，还有雇员、公务员雇员。 And whilst we were dealing with the same counterparty, the same pension fund, some of their constituents, some of the underlying boards, disagree on the approach to take there.</p><p> So we&#39;ve experienced that firsthand, that within one given investor or asset owner, there could be some divergence. And very often now I can say, because there was a bit of a misunderstanding of what we were trying to do and what others are trying to do.</p><p> So I&#39;m hopeful that with a bit of education, the science-based approach, people will realize that it shouldn&#39;t be a political game. I understand why. I&#39;m not naive. I understand why. But I think the majority should prevail to understand that the asset owners today, the asset managers who can help them deploy the capital, have a historical mission because we will be judged 50 years down the road.</p><p> I mean, people will look back and say, what did you do with the amount of capital that was available back then to effectively direct this capital to where it matters? So I&#39;m trying to take this perspective because effectively we&#39;ve never been in an environment with so much cheap liquidity that could be used purposely.</p><p> So you talked about ESG ratchets where people get better rates if they hit certain metrics. And you talked a little bit about agriculture, regenerative agriculture. Explain for those of us not familiar with that, what is regenerative agriculture? What is the focus? What do you want to accomplish with it? Is it just carbon capture or is it more?</p><p> CHABRAN: It&#39;s the whole chain. I mean, it&#39;s the fact that soil goes without saying is a scarce resource that needs to be maintained in a way to be able to keep on producing in a way that for the next generation, you don&#39;t look back and you leave a brown soil full of fertilizer or others that will not be able to generate the same quality of product for the future generation at a time where you&#39;ll have to feed much more people.</p><p> So the technique here, very similar to the climate approach we took five years ago, is really about finding entrepreneurs and the companies who have a solution for soil, effectively a fertility, let&#39;s say, or some technique. You know, it&#39;s not really the agri-tech, as you may be used to, but some techniques have been proven and need this capital to scale, and this capital would not be available otherwise, because it&#39;s not about buying land or acres or forest. It&#39;s not about the agri-tech, which is effectively attracting a lot of capital.</p><p> But these entrepreneurs, these small cap businesses with a proven concept and profitability and they need this capital to scale. So you would be investing 20, 30 percent, taking 23 percent of the company, investing this capital to effectively help scale the business to a size where then you can get to more banking financing, capital market, which is not that open.</p><p> So it&#39;s this whole band, so it&#39;s certainly the case in Europe, we see it more and more here in the US, of this small mid-cap market that doesn&#39;t have, and even more so, going back to your comment about the regional banks, you&#39;ve got part of the financial market structure which is disappearing, and so you need the alternative source of capital, and so that&#39;s where we can be a very relevant tool.</p><p> And that&#39;s for the companies, and the investors also want to allocate there.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: And you partnered with some really interesting companies on this, AXA, the big insurer, and Unilever, the consumer products company, what&#39;s their interest in this sort of sustainable investing?</p><p> CHABRAN: So one comment, as an aside, at TIKEHAU, we&#39;ve always partnered with, or we try as much as we can, to partner with corporates to bring additional skillset. We did that in energy transition, for example, with Total Energies, very early on, &#39;17, &#39;18. We did that in the aerospace, cyber with a bunch of prominent European and global players such as Airbus, Dassault, Safran, Thales, bringing obviously some capital but more importantly some skill sets, some knowledge, some reach so that back to my create not compete, we can tell a different story with investors.</p><p> And as you just mentioned, the last one with Unilever, is the same, is exactly the same approach, which is bringing additional expertise alongside an asset manager, us, financial investors, and there&#39;s no shortage of capital, as we said, out there.</p><p> In that case, one of the largest European insurance company, if not global, and having together a different proposal, fully aligned, with some complementary sourcing to the deal flow. And here again, at first, people were maybe looking at us like, why do you need to bring a corporate? Are there some conflict of interest involved here? And then, a few years down the line, they&#39;re like, well, that&#39;s a very different proposal that we may have heard from older managers and there are plenty out there.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: What&#39;s the conflict of interest if you&#39;re bringing in a consumer product try and make food on a more efficient productive sustainable way.</p><p> CHABRAN: That&#39;s my point, they should be known and they are known but you know there&#39;s you know people at times are a little bit reluctant or resistant you know to change …</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Status quo, it&#39;s really powerful, isn&#39;t it?</p><p> CHABRAN: Voila.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I love this quote of yours I have to ask you about this. The longer the happy hour, the harder the hangover.</p><p> Explain. Very French.</p><p> CHABRAN: Well that was you know I think that was at Milken&#39;s, at Milken Institute in May 22 and that&#39;s when the interest rates are starting to raise and I think I was telling you earlier I was surprised to see that many people in a surprise because effectively the bar had been open for quite a long time with very cheap liquidity, if I may say, available.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Going back to the financial crisis, the entire period that followed was free booze for everyone.</p><p> CHABRAN: Exactly, and that&#39;s 10 years, if not more. And some of us, I think, had effectively lost sight that liquidity should have a price, and credit has some value. And so effectively, this comment I made was that, yes, people are going to have a hangover of this mispriced, over-leveraged asset they may have bought, invested into, as a consequence of this free liquidity.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So let&#39;s talk about, perhaps, a mispriced asset class that was relying on free liquidity, as we&#39;re recording this, there is a recent Wall Street Journal headline, “Company insiders made millions before the SPAC bust.” What are your thoughts on the SPACs, special purpose investment vehicles? How do you look at those?</p><p> CHABRAN: So we got into SPACs two years ago, hopefully not to follow the herd, but because we saw there a very useful technology that could help some of our private companies, which is what we do, the bulk of what we do is investing with private entrepreneurs, accessing the public market with the support of experienced managers, the operating partners, with the support of experienced financial players.</p><p> And effectively, we very successfully “un-SPACed” some. We took public on Euronext Amsterdam, a great company in the TV content production business, 3 billion turnover, 600 million EBITDA. It&#39;s called FL Entertainment, great entrepreneur, Stéphane Courbit. It&#39;s a real company. Our SPAC is trading at, I guess, 10 bucks or around. A real company. So the issue was not the SPAC as a technology. The issue was the type of company that were trying to access this market opportunistically and rightly so in front of some capital that had been given to SPAC&#39;s promoters and managers.</p><p> Remember that interest rates were negative.</p><p> So SPACs were used by some investors as a vault. Here&#39;s some cash.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Getting 5 percent.</p><p> CHABRAN: Exactly. I&#39;ll make up for the interest shortfall and I have the option to opt out.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So it was a guaranteed higher yield, I won&#39;t say high yield, but higher yield bonds with an equity option at the end, if you like the equity company, you can stay with it. Saba Capital is one, a few others did the same thing.</p><p> CHABRAN: The technology itself was excess of cash, interest rates are at zero, I get negative cash, negative interest on my cash account, so here&#39;s the cash and I may opt out.</p><p> What we tried to do in what we did, and some work, although we decided to give back the capital because back to my skin in the game approach, the one we decided to return the capital that was last month, we had 150 million plus of our own capital committed to it.</p><p> So rather than chasing the cheap option with the view of hopefully making the return embedded with the option, we&#39;re like, first and foremost, we&#39;re depleting our capital. The opportunity is not there. We&#39;re not going to deploy our capital for the sake of it.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: This comes back to skin in the game. When you&#39;re a co-investor with your LPs, you don&#39;t make dumb decisions because, hey, we have the cash. We might as well spend it.</p><p> CHABRAN: I think so. So that was just I think misuse of an interesting technique with some investors and a misuse of interesting techniques for the wrong company.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So I read a piece recently, a research piece that said Brexit may have taken as much as 5 percent off the total GDP of the United Kingdom. You worked in London, you&#39;re now in New York, originally from Paris. Does that sound realistic? What was the impact of Brexit on the UK, and who has stepped into the void that Brexit teed up?</p><p> So first of all, that&#39;s a decision that was made by the British people, and I will not comment on the rationale beyond that. I read the same studies that you mentioned, and every day I would talk to some friends, entrepreneurs in Europe telling me how challenging it has become when just to move goods and things into, and just trading with the UK.</p><p> The one part I can comment on was the whole debate around the future of the city of London as a preeminent financial place, global but obviously European.</p><p> What I can tell you Barry, is since the world reopen and you can travel again, I&#39;m actually going back more often to London than to Paris nowadays, which is the headquarter of my firm. Why that? Because London remains a critical business center for financial services.</p><p> There are some challenging associated with some regulation in the way you have to trade and why people and banks had to open or export some branches onto the continent. And I understand why and the technicalities. But when it comes to the cosmopolitan nature of London, attracting global talents, and as much as, I&#39;m French, and Paris has been doing a tremendous job in attracting talents and firms, but the scale is such that I wouldn&#39;t bet against London as a financial center. So we have to cope with technical aspects, regulation, cost of doing business for some has become very punitive if you don&#39;t have the scale.</p><p> And that&#39;s why if I&#39;m a bit selfish in the approach, we were fully equipped on the continent to start with. We&#39;re now moving back more aggressively into London because we were less over-exposed when many people are doing the contrary.</p><p> People are trying to reduce their investment allocation to the UK, their workforce in the UK. So we&#39;re trying to be a bit contrarian and taking advantage of that.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So people overreacted in one direction, creates opportunities.</p><p> CHABRAN: Maybe.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Europe is dealing with a war on its eastern border. What has the Russian invasion of Ukraine done in terms of energy supplies and just the entire relationship of Europe with Russia?</p><p> CHABRAN: Well, it&#39;s a complicated one, it&#39;s a very sad one because, well, I can tell you, Barry, sitting here in the US, and when I talk to friends, family over there, the perception of the war is very different from one side to the other, because the reality that it&#39;s two hours away from many of the Western European capital and the perception, the feeling with the population is very different.</p><p> So having said that, remember a year ago when the war started, obviously the concern about energy, independence, sustainability was front and center. That was, I think, the silver lining of the situation to put more light and focus on accelerating part of the transition and in itself that was an encouraging step.</p><p> Looking backwards a year or 18 months now into this situation, it&#39;s “not as bad” quote unquote, on the energy side, which is good news. But the whole situation, which I think we are unfortunately stuck with for a relatively long period of time, as creating a lot of uncertainty in the region and beyond, but also by the same token a lot of political willingness to move quicker. And the response, if you remember, that the European government made right after the war, they made more progress in a matter of a few weeks than we had in a few years. And so at times it&#39;s effectively when the essential is at stake that people can react constructively.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So the concern, aside from all the humanitarian tragedy of the invasion, was oil prices would spike, it would eventually lead to a recession in Europe. But a lot of Europe seems to have avoided that.</p><p> What are your thoughts about greater Europe tipping into a recession? And pretty clear parts of Europe have slowed down dramatically because of the increased costs and dealing with the war. What does the environment in Europe look like to you?</p><p> So not dissimilar to what we&#39;re experiencing here in the US and the reentering of production capacity, we&#39;re seeing that in many countries across Europe. Reindustrialization has been probably the most popular world of politicians lately, not only because you need to demonstrate less dependency to outside market. The whole deglobalization theme, I think it was accelerating by this whole situation.</p><p> And so for politicians, it&#39;s a way to show a direction for the population. It&#39;s a new paradigm, a new software. And coming back to what we do for a living, asset manager, it&#39;s a great frame in finding ways to allocate, reallocate, working with global investors to attract more capital in certain countries, for certain industries. It&#39;s not happening overnight, but you can make it happen fairly quickly, fairly quickly being a matter of months.</p><p> If you&#39;ve got all these stars aligned from the political direction to the population adhesion and then the capital allocation. I&#39;m hopeful and I&#39;m optimistic that that could be the silver lining of the whole situation, as dramatic the situation can be.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So you have offices in Asia, if we&#39;re de-globalizing to some degree, and China has been the big industrial driver of much of the world, what does it mean for investing in Asia generally, but more specifically China?</p><p> CHABRAN: So what we&#39;ve been doing in Asia, first out of Singapore, where we started eight, nine years ago in Singapore, and then Korea and Japan. We don&#39;t have any presence in China, as a matter of fact. And the dialogue we had with these investors locally was really about attracting them to some of our existing strategies in Europe or in the US.</p><p> Asia is, I have the chance to go back there from time to time, and each time I&#39;m there I found local economies that have been transformed. If you look at Singapore, what it was when we first moved there, and eight years later, that&#39;s a global hub. Like a global hub with all the consequences you&#39;re reading every day. The Bloomberg news, the price of real estate, and the numbers of family offices who moved from Hong Kong, from part of the Middle East to open there for the very same reason that you have created a great talent hub, a very business-friendly environment. You&#39;ve got the most sophisticated sovereign wealth funds in the world. We were lucky enough to have Temasek backing us as early as 2016. They&#39;ve been a great partner ever since. Great marketplace.</p><p> The way we look at our Singapore operations today, we have a headquarter, Paris, and we have three global hubs, New York, London, Singapore. And out of these hubs, then you can reach on a global basis first investors and effectively attracting them where we think there is an interesting investment proposal and also creating investment opportunities when you&#39;ve got this supply-demand imbalance.</p><p> Again, it all comes down to supply-demand and how we can best take advantage of that.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really interesting. So let&#39;s jump to our favorite questions that we ask all of our guests, starting with what have you been streaming these days? What&#39;s been keeping you informed and entertained, either podcast or Netflix or whatever?</p><p> CHABRAN: One I like and I recommend, because that&#39;s being produced by this company we backed that we took, we helped take public a few months ago, is the “Peaky Blinders” that&#39;s great entertainment. Not only because I love this whole story about the villain and the gangsters and all that, but more importantly because that&#39;s great content.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Is that Netflix or Amazon?</p><p> CHABRAN: It&#39;s a Netflix one. It&#39;s a Netflix one. I strongly recommend and produce by our friend at FL Entertainment.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really interesting. So who were your mentors? Who helped to shape your career?</p><p> CHABRAN: So few of them are senior people I worked for when I was a young analyst and associate, because every one of them in their own different approach helped me challenge the fact that we are going on our own at a relatively young age for this business. Some of them telling us, “Well, it&#39;s either too late or too early for good or bad reasons.” And on the contrary, people saying, which was less, the case is in Europe than it can be the case here in the US, there&#39;s never a good time and you should give it a go.</p><p> And so many of them were finance professional, most of the time in investment banking, and still remain friends. Some of them joined us, by the way, along the way at TIKEHAU. And that&#39;s one thing that obviously was very valuable when you start your own venture firm.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: What are some of your favorite books? What are you reading right now?</p><p> CHABRAN: So two books I&#39;ve started, very different. The first one, I was lucky to attend one of the, again, Mike Milken&#39;s, you know, event, you know, recently both in LA and then later on, and as you know, he&#39;s extremely focused on healthcare. And the whole focus is putting through his institute and all the philanthropy around there.</p><p> And the book is called “Faster Cures, Accelerating the Future of Health” by Mike Milken. It&#39;s something which is fascinating because in our job day to day, it&#39;s really short term. And when you step back a bit and you look a little bit of these demographic issues, we touch base on some of those issues, energy and all that, but the demographic is probably the most challenging one.</p><p> And even if it&#39;s 50, 75 years from now, I think we should start factoring in many of that in today&#39;s decision.</p><p> And the other book, more recent, I was lucky to meet a French professor in Boston who&#39;s a teacher both at HBS and HKS. She&#39;s been there for 20 years. Her name is Julie Battilana. And the last book is called “Power for All” And it&#39;s all about the relationship to– I wouldn&#39;t say even power, but if effectively power is about having an influence on making someone else change behavior, how it&#39;s not only top down and the way we may have learned it, and how we should with a new generation, in a new cycle, and the perspective of things that are critical to me, which are democracy, but also capitalism, which is fueling many of that.</p><p> How do you reconcile all that, and it&#39;s a worthwhile reading.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Sounds interesting. Our last two questions, what sort of advice would you give to a recent college graduate who is interested in a career in either private equity or investing?</p><p> CHABRAN: Well, I would send him some of the mottos where you&#39;re seeing everyday at TIKEHAU Capital. Be curious, think out of the box, be on the ball, think big. I will share that with them because that&#39;s one thing that doesn&#39;t change. Technology may change, but interpersonal skill set and being hungry, I think that&#39;s what matters.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Interesting, and our final question. What do you know about the world of investing today? You wish you knew 25 or so years ago when you were first getting started.</p><p> CHABRAN: Never take anything for granted.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Thank you so much for being so generous with your time, Mathieu. We have been speaking with Mathieu Chabran, co-founder of TIKEHAU Capital.</p><p> If you enjoy this conversation, well, be sure and check out any of the other 500 or so discussions we&#39;ve had over the past eight or so years. You can find those at iTunes, Spotify, YouTube, wherever you find your favorite podcast.</p><p> Sign up for my daily reading list at ritholtz.com. Follow me on Twitter @ritholtz. Follow all of the Bloomberg family of podcasts on Twitter @podcast.</p><p> I would be remiss if I did not thank the crack team that helps put the conversations together each week. My audio engineer is Sebastian Escobar. My producer is Paris Wald. Atika Valbrun is our project manager. Sean Russo is my head of research. I&#39;m Barry Ritholtz. You&#39;ve been listening to Masters in Business on Bloomberg Radio.</p><p></p><p style="text-align: center;"> ~~~ </p><p></p><p><iframe style="width: 100%; max-widt